  "diary": "Woke up to gray skies but felt oddly energized. The Ballard Farmers Market was exactly what I needed—wandered through the stalls, talked to a farmer about heirloom tomatoes, grabbed some peonies that are now sitting in a vase by my window. Bastille Café smelled like butter and espresso. I sat there longer than planned, just watching people rush past.\n\nBack home, I chopped vegetables with the kind of focus that usually escapes me on Saturdays. The salmon came together easily tonight—nothing fancy, just salt and lemon. Spent most of the afternoon sketching pottery ideas and transit maps, which probably sounds random, but it felt like the right thing to do. The city felt quieter somehow, even though the Mariners game was pulling crowds downtown. I stayed in, let the ambient music drift through the apartment. Satisfied, tired in the good way.",
  "thought_process": "I think I needed to slow down today. Work at the pharmacy can be relentless—constant transactions, constant questions—so Saturday felt like permission to just exist. The overcast weather actually helped; it made being indoors feel intentional rather than like I was missing out. I chose Ballard specifically because it's far enough from my neighborhood to feel like a small adventure, but close enough that I wasn't making a whole production of it. The pottery sketching came from nowhere, really—just something my hands wanted to do while my mind rested. I didn't check work messages until evening, which for me is almost radical. The Mariners crowds happening without me felt fine. I was exactly where I needed to be.",
